<h1 class="page-title">RAI invites Visiting Fellowship applications</h1>		
		




  <div class="node clear-block ">




    
  
  <div class="supermitted"><span class="submitted">by rai on Mon, 28/01/2013 - 09:39</span></div>
   
    <div class="content clear-block">
    
  <p><img alt="VHL" src="http://www.rai.ox.ac.uk/sites/rai/files/VHL interior_1.jpg" style="width: 180px; height: 221px; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; margin: 5px; float: right;" /><strong>The RAI invites applications for Visiting Fellowships for 2013-14.</strong></p>
<p>RAI Visiting Fellows pursue their research on diverse aspects of American history, politics and culture in the Vere Harmsworth Library&rsquo;s outstanding collections of American materials and elsewhere at Oxford University, write books and articles, and engage in the Institute&rsquo;s lively community of scholarship.</p>
<p>The Institute offers the following categories of visiting fellowship:</p>
<p>&bull; Senior Visiting Research Fellowship (SVRF) tenable for one academic year</p>
<p>&bull; Postdoctoral Visiting Research Fellowships (PVRF) tenable for one term</p>
<p>&bull; Associate Visiting Research Fellowships (AVRF) tenable for one academic year</p>
<p>&bull; Vacation Visiting Research Fellowships (VVRF) tenable for one academic year</p>
<p>For details of each visiting fellowship and how to apply please visit: <a href="http://www.rai.ox.ac.uk/fellows/apply">http://www.rai.ox.ac.uk/fellows/apply</a></p>
<p><strong>The deadline for applications is Friday 1st March at noon.</strong></p>
<p>Please pass on this invitation to any colleagues who might be interested in applying for a Visiting Fellowship at the RAI.</p>
<p>Former holders of RAI Visiting Fellowships write:</p>
<p>&ldquo;The Postdoctoral Visiting Research Fellowship proved instrumental in helping to transform a fledgling examination into the interchange between American intelligence activity and diplomacy in the developing world into a fully developed, coherent and intellectually engaging research project. During my time at the RAI, my research agenda began to attract significant attention from scholarly colleagues on both sides of the Atlantic, government policymakers in Britain and the US, and academic publishing houses.&rdquo; Dr Paul McGarr, University of Nottingham, UK.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The programme of seminars and lectures took my breath away and ensured there was always a buzz in the air. And the scholars I met, from all over the world, challenged and stimulated me daily. My time at the RAI was a wonderful intellectual experience.&rdquo; Dr Michael Ondaatje, University of Newcastle, New South Wales, Australia.</p>
</div>



      
         

  </div>





